<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on quality level and terroir. <strong>Premium Right Bank Bordeaux</strong> like Pétrus or Le Pin can evolve magnificently for 20-30 years, while high-quality Napa Valley Merlots typically peak between 10-15 years. Entry-level Merlots are best consumed within 2-4 years to preserve their fresh fruit character.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p><strong>Immediate consumption (0-3 years):</strong> Commercial Merlots, Washington State value bottlings<br>
<strong>Medium-term aging (5-12 years):</strong> Stellenbosch Merlots, mid-tier Bordeaux blends, premium California examples<br>
<strong>Long-term cellaring (15+ years):</strong> Saint-Émilion Grand Cru Classé, top Pomerol estates, cult Napa producers</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Cellar</h3>
<p>Young Merlot displays bright red fruit and firm tannins from compounds like catechins and proanthocyanidins. With proper aging, these tannins polymerize and soften, while primary fruit flavors evolve into complex <strong>tertiary notes</strong>—leather, tobacco, truffle, and dried herbs. The wine's color shifts from deep purple to garnet, then brick-red as anthocyanins break down.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
<p>Store Merlot at a consistent <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity. Position bottles horizontally to keep corks moist, preventing oxidation. Avoid temperature fluctuations exceeding 5°F, which can cause premature aging through repeated expansion and contraction.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p><strong>Proper aging signs:</strong> Sediment formation, color evolution to brick tones, development of earthy complexity while maintaining fruit integration</p>
<p><strong>Spoilage warnings:</strong> Excessive browning in wines under 10 years, volatile acidity creating vinegar-like aromas, or musty cork taint. A properly aged Merlot maintains structural balance even as it gains complexity—the hallmark of successful cellaring.</p>

