    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is dismissing all Merlot based on the "Sideways effect" or assuming cheaper versions represent the entire category. Many wine drinkers also mistake Merlot for a simple, one-dimensional wine and don't explore premium bottlings from regions like Pomerol or Washington State that showcase the grape's true potential. Another mistake is serving it too warm—Merlot should be served at 60-65°F, not room temperature, to maintain its elegant structure and prevent the alcohol from dominating.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which wines are similar to Merlot if I want to explore other varietals?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Côtes du Rhône blends offer similar approachability with more spice character, while Sangiovese provides comparable food-friendliness with brighter acidity and cherry flavors. For those who enjoy Merlot's plush texture, try Grenache-based wines from Southern Rhône or Spanish Garnacha, which share the soft tannin structure but add more herbal complexity. Pinot Noir from warmer climates like California's Central Coast can also appeal to Merlot lovers seeking similar fruit-forward character with lighter body.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I cellar Merlot, and which styles age best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Merlots from Bordeaux's Right Bank can age gracefully for 15-25 years, developing complex tertiary aromas of leather, truffle, and dried fruits. Washington State and premium California Merlots typically peak at 8-12 years, while most commercial-level bottles are best consumed within 3-5 years of vintage. The key indicators for aging potential are balanced acidity, structured tannins, and alcohol levels below 14%—avoid cellaring fruit-forward styles from hot climates that lack the requisite structure.</p>
